**NOTE: After this project was done, COVID-19 progressed at a devastating rate, effecting the lives of millions in tragic and deeply upsetting ways. This project was not meant to trivialise COVID-19 but in fact to try and help people understand the onslaught of data they were starting to see at every news headline.
It was first put together at the start of the first UK lockdown, but the UK data was not as available as US data and so for illustrative purposes this focused on the US.**

The spread of COVID-19 has been accompanied by a barrage of numbers and statistics that are intended to help the public make some quantitative sense of what is happening. However, the general public doesnâ€™t always know how to interpret this type of information. To address this issue, I has created an application that puts COVID-19 into perspective by comparing it to several causes of mortality that are generally more familiar.

Using data from:

- https://app.namara.io                                       - The dataset was 'COVID statistics by US States - Daily updates'
- https://systems.jhu.edu/research/public-health/ncov/        - Current COVID-19 Stats
- https://github.com/CSSEGISandData/COVID-19                  - JHU GIT Python Module
- https://covid19api.com/                                     - Another use of JHU data
- https://worldpopulationreview.com/states/                   - Used for Comorbidity Risks
- https://www.cdc.gov/nchs/data/nvsr/nvsr68/nvsr68_09-508.pdf - CDC PDF for pulling details of historic death stats, and used online tool to extract needed pages and parse to Excel. Then a little bit of data cleanup

I constructed an application that shows, for each state in the US, the mortality rate for various causes of death, including COVID-19. I have also calculated a Risk Value for each state that combines several factors to determine the risk level that a state is at relative to the other states. This risk value combines general wellness data about the population of each state with the spread of the virus in that state. States with more vulnerable populations and higher infection rates are shaded darker on the map.
